Date: 2026-02-10
Issue: Flatpak apps ignoring user fontconfig (JP font priority, missing Unicode blocks)
Symptom: Japanese text rendered with Chinese glyphs; Mathematical Alphanumeric
         Symbols (e.g. 𝘾𝙊𝙉𝙁𝙀𝙎𝙎) displayed as tofu in Zen browser

========== ROOT CAUSE ==========

Flatpak remaps XDG_CONFIG_HOME to ~/.var/app/<app-id>/config/ per app.
The runtime's fontconfig (50-user.conf) uses prefix="xdg" to find user config,
so it looks at ~/.var/app/<app-id>/config/fontconfig/ instead of ~/.config/fontconfig/.
User's ~/.config/fontconfig/conf.d/50-user-jp-fonts.conf is never read.

Previous workaround (FONTCONFIG_FILE global override) bypassed the entire
runtime fontconfig chain, losing default font mappings (sans-serif, etc.)
and breaking <include> directives.

========== TRIALS ==========

1. FONTCONFIG_FILE global Flatpak override → PARTIAL (previous session's fix)

   What:
     Set FONTCONFIG_FILE=/home/aster/.config/fontconfig/fonts.conf in
     ~/.local/share/flatpak/overrides/global

   Why partial:
     Bypasses the runtime's entire fontconfig chain. Loses all default
     font family mappings (sans-serif → DejaVu, etc.). The custom
     fonts.conf must then replicate everything manually. Also, <include>
     directives inside FONTCONFIG_FILE-specified files don't reliably
     load conf.d.

2. <include> inside custom fonts.conf → FAILED

   What:
     Added <include>/home/aster/.config/fontconfig/conf.d</include>
     to fonts.conf, used with FONTCONFIG_FILE override.

   Why failed:
     <include> with absolute paths to conf.d did not load the JP rules.
     FC_DEBUG showed the included rules were not present in the match
     pattern. Root cause unclear — possibly FONTCONFIG_FILE mode
     changes how <include> resolves.

3. Symlink conf.d into app's XDG dir → WORKED (but per-app)

   What:
     $ ln -sf ~/.config/fontconfig/conf.d \
         ~/.var/app/app.zen_browser.zen/config/fontconfig/conf.d

   Why rejected:
     Requires a symlink per Flatpak app. User wants a global fix.

4. flatpak override --filesystem=xdg-config/fontconfig:ro → SUCCESS

   What:
     $ flatpak override --user --filesystem=xdg-config/fontconfig:ro
     (set in ~/.local/share/flatpak/overrides/global)

   Why worked:
     xdg-config/fontconfig is a Flatpak-recognized path that exposes
     the HOST's ~/.config/fontconfig/ into the sandbox. The runtime's
     50-user.conf then finds and loads the user's fonts.conf and
     conf.d/50-user-jp-fonts.conf through its normal prefix="xdg"
     include mechanism. No FONTCONFIG_FILE hack needed.

5. /nix/store:ro filesystem override (for Home Manager symlinks) → SUCCESS

   Date: 2026-02-27
   Context:
     After migrating fontconfig from manual 50-user-jp-fonts.conf to
     Home Manager's fonts.fontconfig.defaultFonts, the conf files in
     ~/.config/fontconfig/conf.d/ became symlinks into /nix/store/.
     xdg-config/fontconfig:ro correctly exposed the conf.d directory,
     but Flatpak couldn't follow the symlinks because /nix/store was
     not accessible inside the sandbox.

   What:
     Added /nix/store:ro to global Flatpak filesystem overrides
     (in services.flatpak.overrides.global.Context.filesystems).

   Why worked:
     Flatpak can now follow HM-generated symlinks through to the
     actual config files in /nix/store.

========== TAKEAWAY ==========

- Flatpak's XDG_CONFIG_HOME remap is WHY user fontconfig is ignored.
- Don't use FONTCONFIG_FILE override — it bypasses the runtime's fontconfig chain.
- The correct global fix: flatpak override --user --filesystem=xdg-config/fontconfig:ro
- This is a known Flatpak limitation (flatpak/flatpak#3947, still open).
- Before inventing workarounds, search for the issue — this solution was
  documented in flatpak/flatpak#4742.
- When using Home Manager with Flatpak, also add /nix/store:ro — HM config
  files are symlinks into the nix store. This wasn't needed when fontconfig
  was managed by dotter (plain files, no symlinks into /nix/store).

